        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Men lose muscle after 40 due to a combination of declining testosterone, anabolic resistance (the body becoming less efficient at building muscle from protein), and typically insufficient protein intake. Without intervention, men lose 1 to 2 percent of muscle mass per year starting around age 40."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is sarcopenia?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Sarcopenia is the clinical term for age-related muscle loss. It begins around age 40 and accelerates after 60. It causes progressive loss of strength, slower metabolism, increased fall risk, and reduced quality of life. It is largely preventable with resistance exercise and adequate protein intake."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Can you reverse muscle loss after 40?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Yes. Research consistently shows that muscle loss after 40 is not inevitable. Resistance training combined with adequate protein intake — 0.7 to 1.0 grams per pound of body weight daily — can preserve and even rebuild muscle mass at any age."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How much protein do you need to prevent muscle loss after 40?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Most research points to 0.7 to 1.0 grams of protein per pound of body weight per day for men over 40 who want to preserve muscle. That is significantly higher than the USDA RDA of 0.36 grams per pound, which was designed to prevent deficiency, not maintain muscle."
        }
      },
